UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/002219968890027X
AB  - In this paper we assume that risk neutral firms provide income insurance to risk averse workers through labor contracts; however, because of (ad hoc) transaction costs, contracts are not fully contingent. Hence, while contracts improve upon the allocation of risk, they entail ex post production inefficiencies relative to a spot market where employment decisions are based upon realizes values of productivity shocks. Given this tradeoff, there exists the possibility that both labor markets can coexist in equilibrium. We analyze the effects of exchange-rate policy on the distribution of agents across labor market arrangements and the expected utility of agents.
